@dkirkby I think this error happens when you have a mismatch in the two kinds of C++ standard libraries.  cf. https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18389799/boost-python-undefined-symbols-error-even-though-the-lib-files-are-linked

Perhaps because anaconda is using a different C++ compiler than you are using to install GalSim. @esheldon ran into similar issues with Anaconda using a different C++ compiler than the native one, which led to various c++11 std library problems.  Not sure if it's exactly the same as what you are seeing here.

He posted a suggestion about installing with Anaconda in #914 that might be helpful, although one of the things he suggested is `conda install boost` which I guess you are already doing, so maybe it's not relevant.  But maybe since this seems not to be scons 3 related, we could move further discussion of this over to that issue.

@mgeplf 

It indeed changes the length of the array. The reason I suggested it is because morphval compares distributions and not pairwise values. By setting nans to zero or other value will lead to artificial peaks in the distribution which will affect the validation.

However, a lovely warning for morphval (or neurom if you think that it would be more suitable) in case of nans could be useful in order to make sure that you are not filtering out values that are triggered from bugs.

