I think this is definitely an issue that we will have to address at some point. Sub-gigabyte, the official protobuf implementations seem to perform acceptably (not great, but good enough), but it's definitely something we've noticed you have to be careful about. For example, we support two mechanisms for serializing tensors (protobuf repeated floats, or a raw string data) but for large data, only the raw string data mechanism is practical.

An alternative to putting tensor data in separate files is to standardize on a container format on top of protobuf which carries the proto, as well as the raw tensor data, e.g., RecordIO. We've wanted to avoid doing this because having models be a single proto is a very clear and easy to understand design, and an extra layer of indirection makes things more complex.

@postrational, are size problems already affecting you, or is this trying to stave off problems in the near future?
